node.text:
This just happened!! While out on our daily walk through the neighborhood we happened to take a different path home than usual and I think it was meant to be 🐥. I’m always on the lookout for nature and today I heard a bunch of baby birds calling out... while I expected them to be up high in a nest I soon realized the sound was below my feet! ⁣
⁣
After inspecting the storm drain we realized there wasn’t another entrance for the momma duck– these babies were officially stuck and alone and needed some help. ⁣
⁣
After a quick call with @paws_wa (the local wildlife rescue group) we decided the best plan of action was to try and find the mom upstream. We didn’t think we had much of a chance of actually finding her but still gave it our best shot, and we’re glad we did! #EarthDayAtHome @siljadanielsen @evydanielsen @enviroparker @king5seattle

node.title: Baby duckies trapped in a storm drain

node.text: This past #EarthDay2019 I went and planted trees with @microsoft and The Nature Conservancy! We’ve got millions of acres of American wilderness to restore, and this project has really done some excellent work. While I was there I learned about some all around cool AI tech helping conservationists plant trees 🌱🌿🌲 #treepotentialproject #AIforEarth #ad

node.title: Earth Day Tree Planting with MSFT!

node.text:
Osprey and prey, and me on top of truck getting the shot. Osprey are a fun species to learn to recognize, they are a tell-tale sign of water nearby (streams, rivers, lakes, ocean) and have a cosmopolitan range so the majority of people on planet Earth may see one in their lifetime! 

Best way to identify them is by the strong white/dark contrast in the face and the sharp bend in their wings as they fly, distinct from most other birds of prey. The nest are also really distinct and often exposed giant piles of sticks, and they love using old telephone or electrical posts like this as a nest!

Me on truck photo cred @jessica_chobot 

#alaska #adventure #naturephotography #birding #osprey #eosr5 #rf100500

node.text:
The Bald Eagle in #alaska, predator and scavenger in the skies. We came upon a nest along the river,  with one teenager-looking scraggly chick I couldn’t get a good look at. Plenty of salmon and leftover fish scraps in the region from the fishing season to keep that chick well fed!

#canonr5 #baldeagle #rf100500 #adventure #travel @discovery

node.text:
My first grizzly bear! Hiked down to the narrow part of the river, pepper spray in hand looking for pools of gathering salmon that the bears could hunt in more easily. Walked along the edge of the rapids on a bear trail, knowing that with the loud sound of the water any corner could have a bear surprise me and me surprise the bear. 

Terrifying? Yes, especially knowing my only escape route would be to the river, which with the class 5 rapids could drown me with my heavy field boots. Worth it? Absolutely.

Finally, in a shallow pool, I saw this golden blond grizzly bear and watched it return to the river every 10-15 minutes to snatch another salmon. More images and videos to come!

node.text:
So many of these beauties around last week to feed on the salmon in the rivers and salmon scraps from fishermen on the shores.
A reminder that bald eagles are one of the most successful conservation stories out there. Illegal shooting and DDT pesticide decimated their population into the 1970s, but through legislation and Americans rallying together they are simply booming. Can’t imagine a North America without them!

Oh and @siljadanielsen made the most amazing wedding cake for them and it had cricket flour in it! 🦗😍

node.text:
75k! So so thankful for my nature and adventure loving community out there. Love every time I get a DM for a bug ID, a new idea, and even when people keep me accountable and moving forward. Many more adventures to come across the world in the second half of this year, get ready for some 🦋🦦🐻🦇🧟‍♂️👻🌿 action.

PS my buddy @johnschell took this photo of me last year and I never had an occasion to post it, so 75k it is!

node.text:
What an encounter! @siljadanielsen and I celebrated the longest day of the year on our local rocky beach yesterday when I saw a quick brown flash out of the corner of my eye dive into some boulders. 
Was I imagining things or did I just catch a glimpse of a river otter? I ran over and saw what could be wet footprints, so I set down my iPhone filming at 2x and backed off to see if whatever was in there would show itself on camera. Sure enough, when we retrieved the camera a few minutes later, not only was there a river otter staring back but it grabs what looks like a sole or other flatfish that it must have just hunted out of the sea!
Now that I know it lives here, I’ll take advantage of being able to document it from a distance to try and film more of its natural behaviors. And for those wondering why a river otter would be in the sea and why this isn’t a sea otter? Sea otters are reliant on healthy kelp forests and river otters didn’t get the memo to stay in rivers and are found all along Seattle’s shores.
